## Investigation Walkthrough

### Phase 1 — Initial Detection: Zeek DNS Anomaly

Zeek's DNS log (`dns.log`) flagged the anomaly automatically via a custom detection script monitoring query length and volume per host.

**Zeek dns.log — suspicious entries:**

```
ts                  uid         orig_h        query                                    qtype  rcode
------------------  ----------  ------------  ----------------------------------------  -----  -----
2024-04-15 09:12:01 C3hD9x...   10.10.5.14   aGVsbG8td29ybGQ.c2.updates-cdn.net       TXT    0
2024-04-15 09:12:31 C3hD9x...   10.10.5.14   dGhpcyBpcyBhIHRl.c2.updates-cdn.net      TXT    0
2024-04-15 09:13:01 C3hD9x...   10.10.5.14   c3QgZm9yIGRucyB0.c2.updates-cdn.net      TXT    0
```

**Immediate red flags:**
- Subdomain labels are base64-encoded strings — not legitimate hostnames
- All queries are for `TXT` records — unusual for normal browsing
- Same source IP (`10.10.5.14`) sending queries every 30 seconds — beaconing pattern
- Domain `updates-cdn[.]net` registered 25 days ago (WHOIS confirmed)

**Zeek custom detection script that fired the alert:**

```zeek
event dns_request(c: connection, msg: dns_msg, query: string, qtype: count, qclass: count)
  {
  if ( qtype == 16 )  # TXT record
    {
    if ( |query| > 40 )  # suspiciously long subdomain
      {
      NOTICE([$note=DNS::Tunnelling_Suspected,
              $conn=c,
              $msg=fmt("Long TXT query: %s", query),
              $identifier=cat(c$id$orig_h)]);
      }
    }
  }
```

