## Containment Actions

1. Blocked `c2.updates-cdn[.]net` and all subdomains at DNS resolver
2. Isolated `DEV-WS-014` at network switch level
3. Invalidated all 12 VPN credentials found in exfiltrated data
4. Deployed Zeek DNS anomaly detection across all network segments
5. Implemented DNS inspection policy — block TXT queries to non-whitelisted resolvers
6. Submitted IOCs to threat intel platform — correlated with Cases 01 and 02

---

## Recommendations

| Finding | Recommendation |
|---------|---------------|
| DNS not inspected for content | Deploy DNS security (Cisco Umbrella / Infoblox) with TXT record anomaly detection |
| No DNS baseline per host | Establish DNS query volume baseline — alert on 10x deviation |
| Iodine not blocked | Application allowlisting — block unsigned executables in AppData |
| 23-day dwell time | Proactive threat hunting cadence — weekly DNS anomaly review |
| VPN credentials exfiltrated | Enforce MFA on all VPN accounts — credentials alone insufficient |

---

## Key Takeaways

- **DNS is not a safe protocol.** Most organisations inspect HTTP/HTTPS but leave DNS completely uninspected beyond basic sinkholing. DNS tunnelling exploits this gap trivially.
- **TXT record queries are almost never legitimate** in a corporate environment. A Zeek detection rule on long TXT queries would have caught this on Day 1 instead of Day 23.
- **tshark + base64 decoding** is a fast, practical way to reconstruct DNS-tunnelled data streams directly from PCAP without specialised tooling.
